# 📦 SUMMARY  
# This command uses Maven plugins to read (parse) your current project version from pom.xml,  
# then automatically increments the patch (last) number of the version by 1, and writes the new version back to pom.xml.  
# Language/Platform: Bash / Maven CLI  
# What you'll learn: How Maven's `build-helper:parse-version` and `versions:set` plugins work together to  
# manipulate version numbers in an automated way.  
# Outcome: Your project's version changes from something like 1.2.3 → 1.2.4 in the pom.xml file.  
# Why this matters: This is crucial in CI/CD pipelines or release processes where you want consistent,  
# automated version bumps without human error.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🧩 COMMAND EXPLANATION  
# ------------------------------  

mvn build-helper:parse-version \                              # ✅ What it does: Runs Maven with the `build-helper:parse-version` goal.  
                                                             # 🧠 Why it matters: This plugin "breaks apart" the current version  
                                                             # (e.g., 1.2.3) into three variables:  
                                                             #   ${parsedVersion.majorVersion} → 1  
                                                             #   ${parsedVersion.minorVersion} → 2  
                                                             #   ${parsedVersion.incrementalVersion} → 3  
                                                             # This is like splitting the version into pieces so we can modify them.  

versions:set \                                               # ✅ What it does: Calls the `versions:set` goal, which lets you change  
                                                             # the project's version to a new value.  
                                                             # 🧠 Why it matters: Without this, Maven wouldn't know that you want to  
                                                             # update pom.xml with a new version. This is the "action step."  

-DnewVersion='${parsedVersion.majorVersion}.${parsedVersion.minorVersion}.${parsedVersion.nextIncrementalVersion}' \  
                                                             # ✅ What it does: Uses the parsed variables from above to build a new  
                                                             # version string. `${parsedVersion.nextIncrementalVersion}` automatically  
                                                             # adds +1 to the patch version.  
                                                             # Example:  
                                                             #   If current version = 1.2.3  
                                                             #   newVersion = 1.2.(3+1) → 1.2.4  
                                                             # 🧠 Why it matters: Automates version bumping so you don't have to  
                                                             # manually edit pom.xml and risk typos.  

versions:commit                                              # ✅ What it does: Saves (commits) the new version into pom.xml.  
                                                             # 🧠 Why it matters: Until you "commit," Maven keeps the change staged  
                                                             # in memory. This command writes the changes permanently so the next  
                                                             # build uses the new version.  

# ------------------------------  
# ▶️ HOW TO RUN / EXECUTE THIS COMMAND  
# ------------------------------  

# 1️⃣ Open a terminal in the root folder of your Maven project where pom.xml is located.  
# 2️⃣ Run the command exactly as above.  
# ✅ What it does: Reads the old version, calculates the new one, updates pom.xml with the new version.  
# 🧠 Why it matters: Ensures your version number moves forward consistently before a new release or build.  

# ------------------------------  
# 🔄 Equivalent PowerShell Command  
# ------------------------------  

# In PowerShell, we need to escape the `$` sign because PowerShell uses `$` for its own variables.  
# Use backticks (`) to escape it so PowerShell passes it correctly to Maven:  

mvn build-helper:parse-version versions:set \
  -DnewVersion=\${parsedVersion.majorVersion}.\${parsedVersion.minorVersion}.\${parsedVersion.nextIncrementalVersion} \
  versions:commit 

# ------------------------------  
# ✅ NOTES / GOTCHAS / TIPS  
# ------------------------------  
# - 💡 Tip: Make sure `build-helper-maven-plugin` and `versions-maven-plugin` are available in your project  
#   (they don't need to be in pom.xml, but Maven must be able to download them from Maven Central).  
# - 💡 Tip: Always review the resulting pom.xml after running this once or twice,
